The worst-case scenario involves a failure or rupture of a one-ton cylinder outside of the Chlorine Storage Room releasing the entire 2,000 pound contents of the cylinder within ten minutes. The distance to endpoint was estimated to be 1.30 miles from the chlorination facility assuming a wind speed of 3.4 miles/hour and an atmospheric stability rating of ?Class F?. The potential population affected by the worst-case scenario was estimated to be 8,500 persons. 



The alternate release scenario involves a potential pipe leak where 1,500 pounds of chlorine gas may be released during a ten minute accidental release. The distance to the endpoint was estimated to be 0.20 miles from the chlorination facility assuming a wind speed of 6.7 miles/hour and an atmospheric rating of ?Class D?. The endpoint determination includes enclosure of the cylinder within the storage room. The potential population affected by the alternate release scenario was estimated to be 200 persons.



Actuation of the Chlorine Gas Detectors is considered to be an active mitigation measure. Additionally, the chlorine gas piping is vacuum tubing connected directly to the chlorine cylinders. A loss of vacuum in the tubing immediately stops the flow of chlorine gas from the cylinders and virtually eliminates the possibility of a chlorine release due a piping leak. The Salem Water Treatment Plant is equipped with a Chlorine Gas Scrubber, which is also considered to be an active mitigation measure.



The Salem Water Treatment Plant RMP has the key elements listed below. These elements are aimed at preventing a chlorine release from the chlorination system.



* High level of operator training and maintenance training;

* An established preventive maintenance program;

* Implementation of an audit and inspection program;

* Use of effective written operating procedures;

* Implementation of an employee participation program;

* Use of emergency air supply and cyl

inder leak kits;

* Use a of chlorine gas scrubber;

* Performance of process hazard analysis and compliance auditing procedures;

* Use of process alarms and emergency shut down procedures;

* Annual chlorine safety training by the chlorine supplier; and 

* Quarterly demonstration and practice sessions using emergency air supply.



No accidental releases of chlorine gas have occurred at the two existing Salem Water Treatment Plants in the past five years. The new Salem Water Treatment Plant will be placed into service in February 2005.



An emergency response plan is established and is coordinated with the City of Salem LEPC. The plan includes plant evacuation procedures, emergency notification procedures for first responders, and a general public notification plan. Plant evacuation drills are performed in accordance with 29 CFR 1910.38. Emergency response drills are performed in accordance with LEPC schedules.
